Flow control:
To understand flow control, we need to know:
RIP : register instruction pointer, is a important register, you never manually mov value into it, it holds the address of next instruction the cpu will executed
-- Normally, the CPU just adds a few bytes to RIP after every instruction to move to the next line.
(
Why :
Sequential Code Flow: Most code is executed in order (top to bottom). Automatically adding the instruction length to RIP is the most efficient way to proceed to the next line without needing a specific "jump to next line" instruction.
Variable Instruction Lengths: x86-64 instructions are not a fixed size; they can vary in length. The CPU decodes the current instruction first to determine its size, then adds that specific length to RIP.
Performance (Pipelining): Modern CPUs use pipelines to fetch multiple instructions ahead of time. Knowing the next address (RIP + length) allows the processor to fetch subsequent instructions from the cache while the current one is still executing.
Exceptions (Control Flow): If the instruction is a jump, branch, or function call, the CPU overrides this default increment and sets the RIP to a new address. Otherwise, it defaults to the next sequential address.
Position Independent Code (PIC): In 64-bit mode, the CPU uses "RIP-relative addressing." The instructions use the current RIP as a base address to find data, which allows code to run regardless of where it is loaded in memory.
)
-- Instructions like ret, jmp, and call are special because they are the only ways to "force" a new value into the RIP to change where the code is running. ( which is flow control )

How call and ret Work Together
These two instructions are just a "polite" way to jump to a function and come back. 

when it start to call my_function:
It pushes the address of the very next line (the "return address") onto the stack.
It then jumps (changes RIP) to my_function location.
then when it ret:
It pops whatever is on top of the stack and puts it directly into the RIP.
The CPU then looks at RIP and starts executing code from that new address.
--
RIP-Relative Addressing
In 64-bit Windows, programs can be loaded into different parts of memory every time they run (a security feature called ASLR). 
Because the absolute address of secret_code might change, we use RIP-relative addressing.
lea rax, [rel secret_code]: 
rel: A keyword (often used in NASM) that forces Position-Independent Code (PIC) by using an offset relative to the current Instruction Pointer (RIP).
-> This tells the assembler: "Calculate where secret_code is relative to where we are right now (the RIP) and put that address into rax"
